reviewDescription: This is an initial impression. I  using these primarily for MMA work -mainly boxing/kickboxing training. I like the design pattern on the soles which should help with pivots and  turns. The shoes are extremely light weight - probably too light weight - which if I did only grappling/wrestling on mats would be great. However they are so light weight and thin I worry about their durability for heavy boxing training on concrete. I pulled out the glued in wafer thin inserts and added Superfeet carbon insoles to add some notable comfort. The tongue is very large. I replaced the laces with lace-less silicone ties to make them to slip on and off.  I wish there was something like this shoe but made with leather and a thicker base/insole.  They will do I guess for a while, better than running shoes for boxing training.

reviewDescription: I saw these and thought they were hilarious so I had to get them. They are pretty neat, and attach easily to your crocs. breadCrumbs: Clothing, Shoes & Jewelry › Men › Shoes › Boots › Rain
reviewDescription: DELIVERYThese boots are advertised as work boots—protective footwear to stomp through mud, feces, water, muck, compost, and whatever other wet, nasty goop Mother Nature can throw at me. I ordered them based on the reviews. I imagined the shipping label would be welded to the boots, shipped via mule (who would wear the boots), and then blasted onto my property from 1/4 mile away with a boot cannon, ultimately landing unscathed on my front porch where their sheer ruggedness would scare any cowardly porch pirate away.You can imagine my horror when I received a box large enough to ship live chickens, and stuffed with approximately ten feet of plastic bubble wrap. My immediate thought was, "can these not survive the journey in the back of a UPS truck?" I was decidedly unimpressed. I received an expensive battery backup system yesterday that had far less packaging.MISLEADING DESCRIPTIONOnce I dug the boots out of all the plastic, I immediately gave them a squeeze to check those steel toes. It turns out, there's no steel. Now I see the product description says "steel toe style", which is a clever way of separating me from my money when I shop online before finishing my morning coffee. You got me, you sneaky snakes. Good one. Har, har.ACTUAL USEI'm living under this California bomb cyclone, so all disappointment aside, I had work to do. First I slipped the boots on barefoot. The boot liner was comfortable enough that I can see myself jumping out of bed and putting these on without stopping to find socks. But, I didn't want to stink them up or cause any unnecessary abuse to my feet, so I put on standard cotton tube socks and tried them on again. I wear men's size 10.5 shoes, so I ordered the boots in size 11. Perfect—not too loose, not too tight, and plenty of room in the leg to tuck in my pant legs.I marched out into my storm saturated yard where I worry about slipping. The first step outside is onto a rain-slick redwood deck covered in chicken poop. Not a problem; the grippy soles kept me secure and upright. I proceeded to march through mud, dog doo (accidentally), and compost heaps. The boots kept a firm grip on all that slippery ground, allowing me to focus on my task. I don't drive a tractor, so I can't speak to how the boots work with pedals and foot levers, but for walking, they get the job done.FINAL THOUGHTSRead the description carefully. They're inexpensive, so you can't really go wrong. The treads are very grippy and your feet will stay dry. But if you're looking for something to keep with your bug out bag in case of zombies, don't count on these. Between the misleading product description and the gross amount of plastic packaging, I will be a lot more careful about selecting my next pair of work boots and buy something that is more walk and less talk.
reviewTitle: The seller has no confidence in these boots. My feet, however, were not disappointed.

reviewDescription: That is how it feels in hot and humid Southwest Florida especially during the summer.  Our growing season is all year around with just a bit less growth in what some may call the "winter months".  So I spend a lot of time in the wetlands surrounding our property trying to keep the invasive plants under control while avoiding the spikes, thorns, fire ants, poison ivy, and foot fungus that can become problems.I needed a lightweight yet durable rubber boot that was easy to put on (at 70 years of age) that would stand up to the various obstacles I encounter each day.  Having the price be reasonable was also a big selling point since if I liked them, which I do, having an unexpected encounter with something sharp and hidden in the water would simply result in ordering another pair.Basically what you have here is a rubber snow boot like you would wear up north to keep your feet dry during storms.  The big problem down here is simply the high ground water level compounded by tropical storms in the rainy season which tends to even keep your lawn soaked.  Wearing these boots have kept me comfortable and dry while avoiding the flora and fauna problems that our wetlands challenge you with.

reviewDescription: Tried and returned 3 rainboots. The first was a well known British brand, probably durable but rather heavy. The second pair from USA were cute but the arch did not work. Admittedly, these are PVC and not rubber, and that is why they are lighter than the previous rubber boots I tried. Time will tell if they are durable but they felt comfortable enough and neither stiff nor floppy. I wear Women's size 6.5 Wide or 7 in shoes and was looking for simple galoshes to wear in a downpour. I also wanted to tuck my pant legs into the boots. I ordered the Men's size 5 and there is some wiggle room in the toe area but the ankles don't slip out when I walk. I may try an additional insole besides wearing with socks. There was no pressure on the arch of my foot. The width is perfect for me but may not be right for a woman with narrow feet. The sole of the boot is thick with seemingly good traction. The shank is reasonably flexible and allows you to easily glide your foot into the boot.I had a minor peeve. The information tag had been attached to the boots with those plastic connector filaments and left a tiny pinhole near the top edge of each shank. breadCrumbs: Clothing, Shoes & Jewelry › Men › Shoes › Boots › Rain
reviewDescription: DELIVERYThese boots are advertised as work boots—protective footwear to stomp through mud, feces, water, muck, compost, and whatever other wet, nasty goop Mother Nature can throw at me. I ordered them based on the reviews. I imagined the shipping label would be welded to the boots, shipped via mule (who would wear the boots), and then blasted onto my property from 1/4 mile away with a boot cannon, ultimately landing unscathed on my front porch where their sheer ruggedness would scare any cowardly porch pirate away.You can imagine my horror when I received a box large enough to ship live chickens, and stuffed with approximately ten feet of plastic bubble wrap. My immediate thought was, "can these not survive the journey in the back of a UPS truck?" I was decidedly unimpressed. I received an expensive battery backup system yesterday that had far less packaging.MISLEADING DESCRIPTIONOnce I dug the boots out of all the plastic, I immediately gave them a squeeze to check those steel toes. It turns out, there's no steel. Now I see the product description says "steel toe style", which is a clever way of separating me from my money when I shop online before finishing my morning coffee. You got me, you sneaky snakes. Good one. Har, har.ACTUAL USEI'm living under this California bomb cyclone, so all disappointment aside, I had work to do. First I slipped the boots on barefoot. The boot liner was comfortable enough that I can see myself jumping out of bed and putting these on without stopping to find socks. But, I didn't want to stink them up or cause any unnecessary abuse to my feet, so I put on standard cotton tube socks and tried them on again. I wear men's size 10.5 shoes, so I ordered the boots in size 11. Perfect—not too loose, not too tight, and plenty of room in the leg to tuck in my pant legs.I marched out into my storm saturated yard where I worry about slipping. The first step outside is onto a rain-slick redwood deck covered in chicken poop. Not a problem; the grippy soles kept me secure and upright. I proceeded to march through mud, dog doo (accidentally), and compost heaps. The boots kept a firm grip on all that slippery ground, allowing me to focus on my task. I don't drive a tractor, so I can't speak to how the boots work with pedals and foot levers, but for walking, they get the job done.FINAL THOUGHTSRead the description carefully. They're inexpensive, so you can't really go wrong. The treads are very grippy and your feet will stay dry. But if you're looking for something to keep with your bug out bag in case of zombies, don't count on these. Between the misleading product description and the gross amount of plastic packaging, I will be a lot more careful about selecting my next pair of work boots and buy something that is more walk and less talk.
reviewTitle: The seller has no confidence in these boots. My feet, however, were not disappointed.

reviewDescription: I used these recently to go walk around in tide pools and they held up great! I did feel the coldness of the water through the boots but my feet stayed completely dry, even when I stood and walked around in calf-deep water. They were comfortable to walk in as well and they were grippy enough that I didn’t slip on rocks.

breadCrumbs: Clothing, Shoes & Jewelry › Men › Shoes › Boots › Rain
reviewDescription: I bought a pair of size 11 for myself, love them. Great fit. I wear 10/10.5 normally in shoes. I talked my wife into buying a pair - she was NOT willing at first. She finally ordered a size 9. She wears a size 8/8.5 women's WIDE shoe and a size 7.5/8 in men's regular in sneakers. She said these are NOT for people with wide calves. She has "athletic" calves, and needs wide calf boots. Solved the problem, though, by ordering extra long knee socks so they don't rub her legs. Now she wears them everywhere outside. She is an avid gardener and is building a big vegetable garden as well as a woodland garden of flowers and such. She tromps all through the wet ground, dry ground, leaves, everything.She wanted me to add - Dunlop assured her through email that they are latex free. They were fast and thorough in replying to her - even contacted one of the chemists to give a reply! AWESOME JOB DUNLOP! She has had no issues with the boots causing any allergic reaction. We can't guarantee all others will feel the same, but maybe this gives some comfort to those searching. Email them and ask for yourself before buying!She also added she wishes they came in half sizes. She feels the 9 is a bit loose on her feet, which slide a little in the boot while doing heavy yard work. She is going to add an extra insole to see if that helps. But otherwise great fit.Over all, both pairs are WELL WORTH the money. She is planning to order an extra set for BOTH of us as soon as possible. Thanks Dunlop!
reviewTitle: Good fit in the foot, but not for wide calves; Also - love they are latex free.

reviewDescription: I am new to this brand and saw them on a friend. He recommended them. I am so impressed so far. They only come in whole number sizes. I need a 10.5 - so I thought they may not work. But, after pulling the fasteners tighter and tying a new knot on each side, it works like a champ.The ONYL real issue is they have TOO MANY styles to choose from. I just went with the one that looks like it would be the most suitable to my manner of dress. They are super comfortable - and VERY light-weight. It actually threw off my feet a bit at first. I kept tripping - i'm used to much heavier shoes. SO, be aware of that. They are supposedly hand-washable as well as machine washable. I can see that being true.They can be bent in half and retain their shape immediately after (not that that matters).So, bottom line, if you can afford them, go get them. They have WAY more styles at their own website Amazon only seeks a few for some reason.

breadCrumbs: Clothing, Shoes & Jewelry › Men › Shoes › Boots › Rain
reviewDescription: I've tried many boots. None work unless I put wax on them. I don't want to. I thought these would be great because they said non-slip but after buying them I realized quickly that they were not. After carefully rereading the description they also say that the boots do not withstand oils or chemicals. By chemicals I assume the slightest amount of soap. Slipping while scrubbing cars is dangerous. Efficiency drops by about 30% or more. Then my pants get so full of sweat sometimes that I feel like they get the fabric at the top of these boots wet enough to get my socks wet and then my feet. I haven't had boots that got more water in them while wearing pants. How? Why? I don't know, I'm not a scientist, I am a regular person working a crappy job that paid too much for boots. Don't step on diamond plate when it's wet while wearing these. You might get hurt.
reviewTitle: Not for a Car Wash Worker
